    <h2>Negotiating with Different Styles</h2>
    <p>
      Understanding how different negotiation styles interact can help you adapt your approach and navigate potential conflicts more effectively.
    </p>
    
    <div class="interaction-grid">
      <div class="interaction-card">
        <h3>When You Meet a Competing Style</h3>
        <div class="interaction-content">
          <h4>Characteristics You'll Notice:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Direct, assertive communication</li>
            <li>Focus on their own goals and positions</li>
            <li>Comfort with confrontation</li>
            <li>Emphasis on winning</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h4>Effective Strategies:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Be clear and direct about your own interests</li>
            <li>Support your position with objective criteria</li>
            <li>Don't yield to pressure tactics</li>
            <li>Focus on problem-solving rather than competing</li>
            <li>Take breaks if emotions escalate</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="interaction-card">
        <h3>When You Meet an Accommodating Style</h3>
        <div class="interaction-content">
          <h4>Characteristics You'll Notice:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Focus on relationship preservation</li>
            <li>Willingness to yield on substantive issues</li>
            <li>Discomfort with conflict</li>
            <li>Concern for others' needs</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h4>Effective Strategies:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Build rapport and trust before addressing substantive issues</li>
            <li>Show appreciation for their flexibility</li>
            <li>Help them articulate their own interests</li>
            <li>Be careful not to exploit their accommodating nature</li>
            <li>Encourage them to share concerns they might be hesitant to express</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="interaction-card">
        <h3>When You Meet an Avoiding Style</h3>
        <div class="interaction-content">
          <h4>Characteristics You'll Notice:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Reluctance to engage in direct negotiation</li>
            <li>Changing the subject or postponing discussions</li>
            <li>Physical or emotional withdrawal</li>
            <li>Preference for communicating indirectly</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h4>Effective Strategies:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Create a safe, low-pressure environment</li>
            <li>Use indirect communication methods when appropriate (email for initial ideas)</li>
            <li>Break complex issues into smaller, less threatening parts</li>
            <li>Be patient and allow time for processing</li>
            <li>Emphasize the benefits of resolution versus the costs of avoidance</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="interaction-card">
        <h3>When You Meet a Collaborating Style</h3>
        <div class="interaction-content">
          <h4>Characteristics You'll Notice:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Interest in understanding all perspectives</li>
            <li>Focus on creative problem-solving</li>
            <li>Willingness to share information</li>
            <li>Emphasis on mutual gains</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h4>Effective Strategies:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Be prepared to engage in thorough discussion</li>
            <li>Share your interests and concerns openly</li>
            <li>Bring creative ideas to the table</li>
            <li>Allow sufficient time for the process</li>
            <li>Focus on long-term relationship building</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="interaction-card">
        <h3>When You Meet a Compromising Style</h3>
        <div class="interaction-content">
          <h4>Characteristics You'll Notice:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Focus on finding middle ground</li>
            <li>Pragmatic approach to negotiation</li>
            <li>Willingness to "split the difference"</li>
            <li>Emphasis on fairness and equality</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h4>Effective Strategies:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Look for opportunities to create value before compromising</li>
            <li>Use objective criteria to evaluate proposed compromises</li>
            <li>Be prepared with fallback positions</li>
            <li>Acknowledge their fairness orientation</li>
            <li>Consider packaging issues together rather than handling them separately</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    
